{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633348"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:51:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:51:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17476"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17476"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70741"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10166"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17476"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56207"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5450"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23790"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70741"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA public health researcher is explaining key terminology to medical students during their population health rotation. The discussion focuses on how disease burden is measured in communities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the term morbidity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Duration of illness in a population","State of having a disease or medical condition","Number of deaths from a specific cause","Rate of disease spread in a population","Severity of symptoms in affected individuals"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe term \u003Cstrong\u003Estate of having a disease or medical condition\u003C/strong\u003E correctly defines morbidity. Morbidity describes illness or disease presence in an individual or population, distinct from mortality which refers to death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuration of illness in a population\u003C/strong\u003E describes the length of time a disease affects people rather than the presence of disease itself.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENumber of deaths from a specific cause\u003C/strong\u003E refers to mortality statistics rather than disease occurrence.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERate of disease spread in a population\u003C/strong\u003E describes transmission dynamics or incidence rather than the state of being ill.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeverity of symptoms in affected individuals\u003C/strong\u003E measures the intensity of disease manifestations rather than the presence of disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding morbidity is crucial for public health planning as it helps quantify disease burden in populations. Morbidity can be measured as either prevalence (total existing cases) or incidence (new cases) in a given time period.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Morbidity refers to the state of being diseased or having a specific illness or condition.","Morbidity can be measured as incidence (new cases) or prevalence (existing cases) in a population.","Morbidity data helps assess disease burden and plan healthcare resources."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56207"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17476"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56207"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T13:38:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T13:38:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10166"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70741"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-24T05:44:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-24T05:44:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta